Given
```cs
static int Example(DayOfWeek value) => value switch
{
    DayOfWeek.Monday => 1,
    DayOfWeek.Tuesday => 2
};
```
Roslyn emits
```cs
static int Test(DayOfWeek value)
{
    if (value != DayOfWeek.Monday)
    {
        if (value == DayOfWeek.Tuesday)
        {
            return 2;
        }
        <PrivateImplementationDetails>.ThrowSwitchExpressionException(value);
        int result = default(int);
        return result;
    }
    return 1;
}
...
[CompilerGenerated]
internal sealed class <PrivateImplementationDetails>
{
    internal static void ThrowSwitchExpressionException(object unmatchedValue)
    {
        throw new SwitchExpressionException(unmatchedValue);
    }
}
```

Which is perfectly fine. However, it would aid JIT with handling such methods if the generated throw helper was annotated with `[DoesNotReturn]`. Currently, it appears to be inlined, which subsequently reduces the likelihood of inlining methods with non-exhaustive switch expressions with missing default clause. 

I understand that this is ideally an issue for JIT to handle, but given the current policy of applying `[DoesNotReturn]` to other throw helpers too, this falls in line with the established practice.

The motivation for this issue is that we are using https://www.nuget.org/packages/StaticCS to great success in performance-sensitive scenarios, which results in switches that are effectively exhaustive for which Roslyn cannot legally elide the default clause (not until we get type unions üôÇ).

